-*----> What about Kekule's infamous derivation of the idea of benzene ring> from a daydream of snakes in the fire biting their tails?  Is thi> specific enough to count?  Certainly it turns up repeatedly in basi> phil. of sci. texts as an example of the inventive component o> hypothesizing.I think the question is: What is extra-scientific about this? It has been a long time since anyone has proposed restrictions owhere one comes up with ideas in order for them to be considerelegitimate hypotheses.  The point, in short, is this: hypotheses anspeculation in science may come from wild flights of fancy,daydreams, ancient traditions, modern quackery, or anywhere elseRussel